    <stitle>530 and DT-466/408 Diesel Engine Service (1994) - CONNECTING RODS, PISTONS, RINGS AND SLEEVES - CYLINDER
        SLEEVE FITTING PROCEDURE - RECONDITIONING
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="9">
        <title>RECONDITIONING</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>NO TITLE</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check the crankcase counterbore depth using the surface gauge or a depth micrometer as
                    follows (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050630">6.30</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ):
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">"Zero" the dial indicator on the crankcase deck.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Move the indicator onto the counterbore ledge and check the depth at four points.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Refer to "
                        <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS</emph>" for coun-terbore depth and maximum variation between
                        the four measurement points.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">If maximum variation between the four points exceeds specifications, resurface the
                        counterbore.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>DEPTH MICROMETER METHOD</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a depth micrometer as follows (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050631">6.31</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ):
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Check the counterbore depth at four points around the crankcase counterbore.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Record the measurements.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Refer to "
                        <emph type="bold">SPECIFICATIONS</emph>", and resurface the counterbore if the maximum variation
                        between measurement points is exceeded.
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050630" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2427" filename="../figeg2/EG2427.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.30.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Dial Indicator</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Counter Bore Ledge</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Crankcase</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050631" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2428" filename="../figeg2/EG2428.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.31.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Depth Micrometer</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Crankcase</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Counter Bore Ledge</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Resurface the counterbore using the counterboring tool,
                    <emph type="bold">ZTSE2514</emph>
                    along with the appropriate cutter head as follows:
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The counterboring tool is a low profile tool which can be used in chassis.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">PRE-SET TOOL BIT</emph>
                        by placing a 0.008 in. to 0.010 in.(0.20 to 0.25 mm) feeler gauge on the O.D. of the cutter head
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE2514-4</emph>. Push the tool bit out until it touches the feeler gauge.
                        Lock the tool bit in place using an Allen wrench as shown in
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050632">6.32</hotlnk>.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">INSTALL THE CUTTER HEAD</emph>
                        <emph type="bold">ZTSE2514-4</emph>
                        onto the driver unit and adapter plate of the counterboring tool. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050633">6.33</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <figure id="ef1050632" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg3034" filename="../figeg3/EG3034.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.32.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Allen Wrench</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Feeler Gauge</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Locking Plate</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. Tool Bit</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050633" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg3035" filename="../figeg3/EG3035.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.33.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Cutting Tool</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Tool Bit</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Feeler Gauge</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. Washers (2)</callout1>
                            <callout1>5. Mounting Bolts (2)</callout1>
                            <callout1>6. Spacer (2)</callout1>
                            <callout1>7. Locking Plate (7)</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">RAISE THE CUTTER HEAD</emph>
                        by pulling the plunger and lifting up on the handle. Mount the counterboring tool assembly to
                        the crankcase as shown in
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050634">6.34</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        . Tighten the cap screw with washers finger-tight than apply 33 lbf-ft. (45 Nm) torque.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">LOWER THE CUTTING HEAD</emph>
                        by loosening locking screws on turn knuckles. Pull plunger up, to desired height. tighten turn
                        knuckle in position and lock in place with lockiong screws.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">SET THE DEPTH OF THE CUT</emph>
                        using one of two methods.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>METHOD ONE (Use graduated marks on tool).</title>
            <para>Use the following steps:</para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen locking screw.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Rotate the adjusting nut in a counterclockwise direction until the nut contacts the
                    driver unit housing.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Back off the adjusting nut by the amount of cut desired.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Each graduated marking equals 0.001 in. (0.025mm). If 0.002 in. (0.050mm) material is to
                            be removed, you must back off the adjusting nut two marks.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten the adjusting nut lock screw.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>NEVER ATTEMPT TO REMOVE MORE THAN 0.002 IN. (0.050mm) MATERIAL AT A TIME.</para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef1050634" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3037" filename="../figeg3/EG3037.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.34.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Handle</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Upper Turn Knuckle</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Lower Turn</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. Crankcase</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>METHOD TWO (Use feeler gauge).</title>
            <para>Use the following steps (
                <emph type="bold">Figure
                    <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050635">6.35</hotlnk>
                </emph>
                ):
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen locking screw.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert an appropriate size feeler gauge (0.002 in.{0.05 mm} max.) between upper and
                    lower turn knuckle. Rotate upper turn knuckle until feeler gauge is just held in place.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tighten the locking screw and remove the feeler gauge.</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">
                        <emph type="bold">CUT THE COUNTERBORE</emph>
                        by rotating handle smoothly in a clockwise direction until unit turns freely and is bottomed out
                        between adjusting nut and top of driver unit housing. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050636">6.36</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remeasure counterbore depth once counterbore has been resurfaced and cleaned up. Refer
                    to "
                    <emph type="bold">Cylinder Sleeve Fitting Procedure</emph>", step one in this section.
                </para>
                <figure id="ef1050635" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3038" filename="../figeg3/EG3038.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.35.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Handle</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Upper Turn Knuckle</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Feeler Gauge</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. Lower Turn Knuckle</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. Crankcase</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef1050636" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="eg3036" filename="../figeg3/EG3036.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 6.36.</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. Handle</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. Upper Turn Knuckle</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. Lower Turn Knuckle</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. Crankcase</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check cylinder sleeve protrusion as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean cylinder bore and crankcase counterbore area.</para>
                    <specpara>
                        <important>
                            <para>TO AVOID DAMAGE TO THE TOOL BIT, NEVER ROTATE COUNTERCLOCKWISE WHEN TOOL BIT IS IN
                                CONTACT WITH COUNTERBORE LEDGE.
                            </para>
                        </important>
                    </specpara>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Place each sleeve in crankcase without O-Rings. Clamp sleeve down using three
                        holding adapters.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the sleeve into its bore and install the holding adapters as shown in
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050637">6.37</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        . Fasten the holding adapters using grade 8 bolts and hardened washers. Tighten the bolts in two
                        stages as follows:
                    </para>
                    <seqlist style="arabic">
                        <item>
                            <para>1. 40 lb-ft. (55 Nm)</para>
                        </item>
                        <item>
                            <para>2. 80 lb-ft. (110 Nm)</para>
                        </item>
                    </seqlist>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using a surface gauge, place the dial indicator tip on the cylinder sleeve flange.
                        "Zero" the indicator and move the block until the indicator tip slides off the flange to the
                        crankcase deck. Record the reading. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef1050638">6.38</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Take readings at three points around the sleeve and use the average reading to
                                determine which shim(s), if any, is needed to bring the cylinder sleeve protrusion
                                within the specification.
                            </para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <figure id="ef1050637" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2429" filename="../figeg2/EG2429.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.37.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Wrench</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Crankcase</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Holding Adapters</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. Counterbore Ledge</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef1050638" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="eg2430" filename="../figeg2/EG2430.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 6.38.</caption>
                        <calloutgroup>
                            <callout1>1. Dial Indicator</callout1>
                            <callout1>3. Sleeve</callout1>
                            <callout1>2. Holding Adapters</callout1>
                            <callout1>4. Crankcase</callout1>
                        </calloutgroup>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Adjust the sleeve protrusion, as follows:</para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Remove the holding adapters and cylinder sleeve.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Clean the top deck of the crankcase and the cylinder sleeve counterbore.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Install the shim(s), as required to bring the protrusion above the crankcase deck
                        within specifications. Refer to
                        <emph type="bold">Figure
                            <hotlnk document="e105_121.xml" xrefid="ef1050639">6.39</hotlnk>
                        </emph>
                        .
                    </para>
                    <specpara>
                        <note>
                            <para>Shims are available as a package consisting of the following:</para>
                        </note>
                    </specpara>
                    <table id="et1050609">
                        <tgroup cols="2">
                            <colspec colname="1" colwidth="90p"/>
                            <colspec colname="2" colwidth="90p"/>
                            <tbody>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>Shim size</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>shim size</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>0.002 inch</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.05 mm</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>0.004 inch</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.01 mm</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>0.010 inch</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.25 mm</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>0.020 inch</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.51 mm</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <entry colname="1">
                                        <para>0.032 inch</para>
                                    </entry>
                                    <entry colname="2">
                                        <para>0.81 mm</para>
                                    </entry>
                                </row>
                            </tbody>
                        </tgroup>
                    </table>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Follow cylinder sleeve installation instructions.</para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
